{"title_page": "Dhammalok Mahasthavir", "text_new": "{{About|a Nepalese Buddhist monk who worked to revive Theravada Buddhism|the Irish-born migrant worker turned Buddhist monk| U Dhammaloka}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Dhammalok Mahasthavir\n|image= Buddhist monk Dhammalok full length.jpg\n|caption = \n|birth_name = Das Ratna\n|alias = Bhikkhu Dhammalok Mahathero, Dharmaloka\n|dharma name = \n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1890|1|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place = Asan Dhalasikwa, [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|1966|10|17|1890|1|16|df=y}}\n|death_place = Ananda Kuti Vihar, [[Swayambhu]], [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n|nationality = [[Nepal]]ese\n|religion = [[Buddhism]]\n|school = [[Theravada]]\n|lineage = \n|title = \n|location = \n|education = \n|occupation = [[bhikkhu|Buddhist monk]]\n|teacher = \n|reincarnation of = \n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|students = \n|spouse = \n|partner = \n|children = \n|website = \n}}\n\n{{Buddhism}}\n\n'''Dhammalok Mahasthavir''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0927\u092e\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0915 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0935\u093f\u0930) (born '''Das Ratna Tuladhar''') (16 January 1890 \u2013 17 October 1966) was a Nepalese Buddhist monk who worked to revive [[Theravada Buddhism]] in [[Nepal]] in the 1930s and 1940s. For this act, he was expelled from the country by the tyrannical [[Rana dynasty|Rana]] regime.<ref>{{cite book| author = Sarah Ethel LeVine| author2 = David N Gellner| title = Rebuilding Buddhism: The Theravada Movement in Twentieth Century Nepal| year = 2005| isbn = 978-0-674-01908-9| page = [https://archive.org/details/rebuildingbuddhi0000levi/page/41 41]| url = https://archive.org/details/rebuildingbuddhi0000levi/page/41}}</ref>\n\nDhammalok was also a writer who contributed to the [[Nepal Bhasa renaissance#Impact|Nepal Bhasa renaissance]]. He worked to promote Theravada Buddhism and Nepal Bhasa braving government persecution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|title=Theravada Buddhism in Modern Nepal|publisher=Lumbini Nepalese Buddha Dharma Society (UK)|accessdate=13 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804160554/http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|archive-date=4 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gellner|first=David N.|title=Three Buddhist Hymns from Nepal|url=http://www.isca.ox.ac.uk/fileadmin/ISCA/ACADEMIC/D_Gellner_publication_files/ThreeBuddhistHymnsfromNepal.pdf|accessdate=17 March 2011|newspaper=Guthi|publisher=Newa Pasa Pucha UK|year=2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928045653/http://www.isca.ox.ac.uk/fileadmin/ISCA/ACADEMIC/D_Gellner_publication_files/ThreeBuddhistHymnsfromNepal.pdf|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nDhammalok (alternative names: Bhikkhu Dhammalok Mahathero, Dharmaloka) was born Das Ratna [[Tuladhar]] at [[Asan, Kathmandu|Asan]] Dhalasikwa, [[Kathmandu]] to a trading family. His father was Kesh Sundar and his mother Bekha Laxmi Tuladhar. Das Ratna engaged in business in [[Tibet]] during his early years and was known by the nickname Baran Sahu (\u092c\u093e\u0930\u093e\u0902 \u0938\u093e\u0939\u0941).<ref>Aniruddha, Bhikshu (July 2004). ''Mahosadha Mahajataka.'' Taipei: The Corporate Body of the Buddha Educational Foundation. Page 3.</ref>\n\nHe was married to Dibya Laxmi with whom he had two sons and a daughter. Grief at the death of his wife and his association with Mahapandit [[Rahul Sankrityayan]] of India drew him towards religion.<ref>Sudarshan, Bhikshu (1970). ''Lumankebahapin'' (\"Memorable Figures\"). Kathmandu: Chwasapasa. Pages 75-84.</ref> His elder son Gaja Ratna too became a Buddhist monk, taking up the name [[Aniruddha Mahathera]].\n\n==Imprisonment and ordination==\n\nIn 1929, Das Ratna went to Sri Lanka for religious study. Returning to Nepal, he lived at the monastery of [[Kindo Baha]] near [[Swayambhu]] where he conducted regular prayer meetings and distributed pamphlets written in Nepal Bhasa appealing for donations. On 6 November 1931, he was arrested and imprisoned for seven days as it was illegal to write in Nepal Bhasa<ref>{{cite book| last = Lienhard| first = Siegfried| title = Nev\u0101r\u012bg\u012bt\u012bma\u00f1jar\u012b| year = 1992| publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publ.| isbn = 978-81-208-0963-5| page = 4 }}</ref> or propagate Buddhism. Subsequently, Das Ratna went to Rangoon, Burma (now [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]) where he lived a year. Returning from Burma, he went to [[Kusinagar]] where he became a novice monk and took the name Dhammalok in 1933.<ref>Mahasthavir, Bhikkhu Dharmaloka (1999). ''A Pilgrimage in China.'' Kathmandu: Bhikkhu Aniruddha Mahasthavir. Page 17.</ref>\n\nDhammalok returned to Kindo Baha, where he began writing a series of books in Nepal Bhasa that challenged traditional thinking. ''Lokay Kuchal Kubyabahar Sudhar'' (\"Reforming Ill Practices and Customs in Society\") and ''Dharmaya Namay Pap'' (\"Sinning in the Name of Religion\") published from [[Varanasi]], India are some of his well-known works. Dhammalok has also translated ''Buddha Charita'', a biography of the Buddha by Asva Ghosh, into Nepal Bhasa from the Sanskrit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kloppenborg|first=Ria|title=Theravada Buddhism in Nepal|url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/kailash/kailash_05_04_03.pdf|accessdate=16 March 2011|newspaper=Kailash|publisher= |date=}} Page 305.</ref> Among his notable books, the travelogue ''Mahachin Yatra'' (\"A Journey to Great China\") was published from [[Kalimpong]] in 1950. Dhammalok received higher ordination in [[Sarnath]] in 1935.<ref>Mahasthavir, Bhikkhu Dharmaloka (1999). ''A Pilgrimage in China.'' Kathmandu: Bhikkhu Aniruddha Mahasthavir. Page 30.</ref>\n\n==Into exile==\n\nIn 1943, Dhammalok established Ananda Kuti Vihar, the first Theravada monastery in modern Nepal, at Swayambhu. It became the center for the Theravada community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|title=Theravada Buddhism in Modern Nepal|publisher=Lumbini Nepalese Buddha Dharma Society (UK)|accessdate=13 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804160554/http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|archive-date=4 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe government declared that the activities of the Theravada monks of spreading Buddhism and writing in Nepal Bhasa were illegal, and on 30 July 1944, eight monks including Dhammalok, [[Pragyananda Mahasthavir]] and [[Kumar Kashyap Mahasthavir]] were expelled from Nepal for refusing to sign a pledge to stop doing so.<ref>Mahasthavir, Bhikkhu Dharmaloka (1999). ''A Pilgrimage in China.'' Kathmandu: Bhikkhu Aniruddha Mahasthavir. Pages 124-125.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dietrich|first=Angela|title=Buddhist Monks and Rana Rulers: A History of Persecution|url=http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm|accessdate=17 March 2011|newspaper=Buddhist Himalaya: A Journal of Nagarjuna Institute of Exact Methods|year=1996|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001124156/http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm|archive-date=1 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The exiled monks first went to [[Kushinagar]], India and then to Sarnath. On the full moon day of 31 November 1944 in Sarnath, they founded Dharmodaya Sabha (Society for the Rise of the Teaching) which published books and a magazine on Buddhism titled ''[[Dharmodaya]]''.\n\nDhammalok spent his exile in India, Tibet and Bhutan, and returned to Kathmandu on 5 June 1946 after the ban was lifted.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Boudddha Bhichhuharu|url=http://50.57.175.244:8001/xmlui/bitstream/10887/638/1/20030518.pdf|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=Gorkhapatra|date=3 September 1946}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Page 7.</ref> From 1946, following pressure from Indian Buddhist societies, the government also allowed publication of literature in Nepal Bhasa after being censored.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hutt|first=Michael|title=Diversity and Change in the Languages|url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/contributions/CNAS_14_01_01.pdf|accessdate=15 March 2011|newspaper=CNAS Journal|publisher=Tribhuvan University |date=December 1986}} Page 10.</ref> Dhammalok devoted his later years to writing. He also worked to develop [[Lumbini]] and [[Kapilavastu (ancient city)|Kapilavastu]], the Buddha's birthplace and family home in southern Nepal.<ref>{{cite web| last =Sakya| first =Ratna Man| url =http://www.nrn.org.np/speeches/rmshakya.html| title =Lumbini - The Birthplace of Lord Buddha| publisher =Non-Resident Nepali Association| accessdate =18 March 2011| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20101225084929/http://www.nrn.org.np/speeches/rmshakya.html| archivedate =25 December 2010}}</ref> Dhammalok died at Ananda Kuti Vihar.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile: Statue of dhammalok.jpg|<div align =\"center\">Statue of Dhammalok at Ananda Kuti Vihar.</div>\nFile: Ananda kuti vihar.jpg|<div align =\"center\">Ananda Kuti Vihar, Kathmandu.</div>\nFile:Kindo baha.jpg|<div align =\"center\">Kindo Baha, Kathmandu.</div>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Banishment of Buddhist monks from Nepal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nepal Bhasa renaissance}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dhammalok Mahasthavir}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kathmandu]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Theravada Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhism writers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male writers]]\n[[Category:Nepal Bhasa writers]]\n[[Category:Language activists]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Nepalese exiles]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a Nepalese Buddhist monk who worked to revive Theravada Buddhism|the Irish-born migrant worker turned Buddhist monk| U Dhammaloka}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|name = Dhammalok Mahasthavir\n|image= Buddhist monk Dhammalok full length.jpg\n|caption = \n|birth_name = Das Ratna\n|alias = Bhikkhu Dhammalok Mahathero, Dharmaloka\n|dharma name = \n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1890|1|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place = Asan Dhalasikwa, [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|1966|10|17|1890|1|16|df=y}}\n|death_place = Ananda Kuti Vihar, [[Swayambhu]], [[Kathmandu]], [[Nepal]]\n|nationality = [[Nepal]]ese\n|religion = [[Buddhism]]\n|school = [[Theravada]]\n|lineage = \n|title = \n|location = \n|education = \n|occupation = [[bhikkhu|Buddhist monk]]\n|teacher = \n|reincarnation of = \n|predecessor = \n|successor = \n|students = \n|spouse = \n|partner = \n|children = \n|website = \n}}\n\n{{Buddhism}}\n\n'''Dhammalok Mahasthavir''' ([[Devanagari]]: \u0927\u092e\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0915 \u092e\u0939\u093e\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0935\u093f\u0930) (born '''Das Ratna Tuladhar''') (16 January 1890 \u2013 17 October 1966) was a Nepalese Buddhist monk who worked to revive [[Theravada Buddhism]] in [[Nepal]] in the 1930s and 1940s. For this act, he was expelled from the country by the tyrannical [[Rana dynasty|Rana]] regime.<ref>{{cite book| author = Sarah Ethel LeVine| author2 = David N Gellner| title = Rebuilding Buddhism: The Theravada Movement in Twentieth Century Nepal| year = 2005| isbn = 978-0-674-01908-9| page = [https://archive.org/details/rebuildingbuddhi0000levi/page/41 41]| url = https://archive.org/details/rebuildingbuddhi0000levi/page/41}}</ref>\n\nDhammalok was also a writer who contributed to the [[Nepal Bhasa renaissance#Impact|Nepal Bhasa renaissance]]. He worked to promote Theravada Buddhism and Nepal Bhasa braving government persecution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|title=Theravada Buddhism in Modern Nepal|publisher=Lumbini Nepalese Buddha Dharma Society (UK)|accessdate=13 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804160554/http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|archive-date=4 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gellner|first=David N.|title=Three Buddhist Hymns from Nepal|url=http://www.isca.ox.ac.uk/fileadmin/ISCA/ACADEMIC/D_Gellner_publication_files/ThreeBuddhistHymnsfromNepal.pdf|accessdate=17 March 2011|newspaper=Guthi|publisher=Newa Pasa Pucha UK|year=2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928045653/http://www.isca.ox.ac.uk/fileadmin/ISCA/ACADEMIC/D_Gellner_publication_files/ThreeBuddhistHymnsfromNepal.pdf|archive-date=28 September 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nDhammalok (alternative names: Bhikkhu Dhammalok Mahathero, Dharmaloka) was born Das Ratna [[Tuladhar]] at [[Asan, Kathmandu|Asan]] Dhalasikwa, [[Kathmandu]] to a trading family. His father was Kesh Sundar and his mother Bekha Laxmi Tuladhar. Das Ratna engaged in business in [[Tibet]] during his early years and was known by the nickname Baran Sahu (\u092c\u093e\u0930\u093e\u0902 \u0938\u093e\u0939\u0941).<ref>Aniruddha, Bhikshu (July 2004). ''Mahosadha Mahajataka.'' Taipei: The Corporate Body of the Buddha Educational Foundation. Page 3.</ref>\n\nHe was married to Dibya Laxmi with whom he had two sons and a daughter. Grief at the death of his wife and his association with Mahapandit [[Rahul Sankrityayan]] of India drew him towards religion.<ref>Sudarshan, Bhikshu (1970). ''Lumankebahapin'' (\"Memorable Figures\"). Kathmandu: Chwasapasa. Pages 75-84.</ref> His elder son Gaja Ratna too became a Buddhist monk, taking up the name [[Aniruddha Mahathera]].\n\n==Imprisonment and ordination==\n\nIn 1929, Das Ratna went to Sri Lanka for religious study. Returning to Nepal, he lived at the monastery of [[Kindo Baha]] near [[Swayambhu]] where he conducted regular prayer meetings and distributed pamphlets written in Nepal Bhasa appealing for donations. On 6 November 1931, he was arrested and imprisoned for seven days as it was illegal to write in Nepal Bhasa<ref>{{cite book| last = Lienhard| first = Siegfried| title = Nev\u0101r\u012bg\u012bt\u012bma\u00f1jar\u012b| year = 1992| publisher = Motilal Banarsidass Publ.| isbn = 978-81-208-0963-5| page = 4 }}</ref> or propagate Buddhism. Subsequently, Das Ratna went to Rangoon, Burma (now [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]) where he lived a year. Returning from Burma, he went to [[Kusinagar]] where he became a novice monk and took the name Dhammalok in 1933.<ref>Mahasthavir, Bhikkhu Dharmaloka (1999). ''A Pilgrimage in China.'' Kathmandu: Bhikkhu Aniruddha Mahasthavir. Page 17.</ref>\n\nDhammalok returned to Kindo Baha, where he began writing a series of books in Nepal Bhasa that challenged traditional thinking. ''Lokay Kuchal Kubyabahar Sudhar'' (\"Reforming Ill Practices and Customs in Society\") and ''Dharmaya Namay Pap'' (\"Sinning in the Name of Religion\") published from [[Varanasi]], India are some of his well-known works. Dhammalok has also translated ''Buddha Charita'', a biography of the Buddha by Asva Ghosh, into Nepal Bhasa from the Sanskrit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kloppenborg|first=Ria|title=Theravada Buddhism in Nepal|url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/kailash/kailash_05_04_03.pdf|accessdate=16 March 2011|newspaper=Kailash|publisher= |date=}} Page 305.</ref> Among his notable books, the travelogue ''Mahachin Yatra'' (\"A Journey to Great China\") was published from [[Kalimpong]] in 1950. Dhammalok received higher ordination in [[Sarnath]] in 1935.<ref>Mahasthavir, Bhikkhu Dharmaloka (1999). ''A Pilgrimage in China.'' Kathmandu: Bhikkhu Aniruddha Mahasthavir. Page 30.</ref>\n\n==Into exile==\n\nIn 1943, Dhammalok established Ananda Kuti Vihar, the first Theravada monastery in modern Nepal, at Swayambhu. It became the center for the Theravada community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|title=Theravada Buddhism in Modern Nepal|publisher=Lumbini Nepalese Buddha Dharma Society (UK)|accessdate=13 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140804160554/http://www.lumbini.org.uk/bd_n_thera_t.html|archive-date=4 August 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe government declared that the activities of the Theravada monks of spreading Buddhism and writing in Nepal Bhasa were illegal, and on 30 July 1944, eight monks including Dhammalok, [[Pragyananda Mahasthavir]] and [[Kumar Kashyap Mahasthavir]] were expelled from Nepal for refusing to sign a pledge to stop doing so.<ref>Mahasthavir, Bhikkhu Dharmaloka (1999). ''A Pilgrimage in China.'' Kathmandu: Bhikkhu Aniruddha Mahasthavir. Pages 124-125.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dietrich|first=Angela|title=Buddhist Monks and Rana Rulers: A History of Persecution|url=http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm|accessdate=17 March 2011|newspaper=Buddhist Himalaya: A Journal of Nagarjuna Institute of Exact Methods|year=1996|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001124156/http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-BH/bh117536.htm|archive-date=1 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The exiled monks first went to [[Kushinagar]], India and then to Sarnath. On the full moon day of 31 November 1944 in Sarnath, they founded Dharmodaya Sabha (Society for the Rise of the Teaching) which published books and a magazine on Buddhism titled ''[[Dharmodaya]]''.\n\nDhammalok spent his exile in India, Tibet and Bhutan, and returned to Kathmandu on 5 June 1946 after the ban was lifted.<ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Boudddha Bhichhuharu|url=http://50.57.175.244:8001/xmlui/bitstream/10887/638/1/20030518.pdf|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=Gorkhapatra|date=3 September 1946}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Page 7.</ref> From 1946, following pressure from Indian Buddhist societies, the government also allowed publication of literature in Nepal Bhasa after being censored.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hutt|first=Michael|title=Diversity and Change in the Languages|url=http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/contributions/CNAS_14_01_01.pdf|accessdate=15 March 2011|newspaper=CNAS Journal|publisher=Tribhuvan University |date=December 1986}} Page 10.</ref> Dhammalok devoted his later years to writing. He also worked to develop [[Lumbini]] and [[Kapilavastu (ancient city)|Kapilavastu]], the Buddha's birthplace and family home in southern Nepal.<ref>{{cite web| last =Sakya| first =Ratna Man| url =http://www.nrn.org.np/speeches/rmshakya.html| title =Lumbini - The Birthplace of Lord Buddha| publisher =Non-Resident Nepali Association| accessdate =18 March 2011| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20101225084929/http://www.nrn.org.np/speeches/rmshakya.html| archivedate =25 December 2010}}</ref> Dhammalok died at Ananda Kuti Vihar.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile: Statue of dhammalok.jpg|<div align =\"center\">Statue of Dhammalok at Ananda Kuti Vihar.</div>\nFile: Ananda kuti vihar.jpg|<div align =\"center\">Ananda Kuti Vihar, Kathmandu.</div>\nFile:Kindo baha.jpg|<div align =\"center\">Kindo Baha, Kathmandu.</div>\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Banishment of Buddhist monks from Nepal]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nepal Bhasa renaissance}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dhammalok Mahasthavir}}\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kathmandu]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Theravada Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Theravada Buddhism writers]]\n[[Category:Nepalese male writers]]\n[[Category:Nepal Bhasa writers]]\n[[Category:Language activists]]\n[[Category:Persecution of Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Nepalese exiles]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dhammalok_Mahasthavir"}
